style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New style="mso-bookmark:_fc97ae53_8584_4c1f_a6db_297550f442ff;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_eda5cb8b_326a_4600_8bf2_b188de7c325e;"></font> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan lines-together;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan lines-together;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;">Other financial instruments including accounts receivable, accounts payable, debt and accrued liabilities are not required to be measured at fair value on a recurring basis. The carrying value of these financial instruments approximates fair value due to their short maturities. Based on borrowing rates currently available to us, with similar terms, the carrying values of capital lease obligations and the revolving credit facility approximate their fair values.<i></i></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><i>Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</i></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;">The majority of our non-financial instruments including inventories, property, plant and equipment and intangible assets are not required to be measured at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is determined to be impaired, it is recorded at its fair value and any difference between its carrying value and fair value is reflected in </font><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;">the consolidated statements of income</font> as an impairment loss. See Note 3 &#8211; Property and Equipment for more information regarding impairment charges related to non-recurring fair value measurements.</font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan lines-together;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><i>Derivative Financial Instruments</i></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We enter into foreign currency exchange forward contracts and currency swaps to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts at June 30, 2012 and December&nbsp;31, 2011. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks. </font></font></p> style="mso-bookmark:_54ba7a65_ce85_4020_b5b6_916862453455;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_ff6aab11_f588_47e7_81ec_b3ca33ea43fc;"></font> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan lines-together;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><i><br /> Undesignated Derivative Instruments</i></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">We may elect to enter into foreign exchange forwards and currency swaps to mitigate the change in fair value of specific assets and liabilities on the balance sheet explained above. These foreign currency exchange contracts are not designated as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging. Accordingly, these undesignated instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net together with the re-measurement gain or loss from the hedged balance sheet position. For purposes of the cash flow statement, the Company classifies the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within the cash provided by operations. </font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The following table presents the amounts affecting the consolidated statements of income for the three months and six ended June 30, 2012 and 2011.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;">During both periods presented, we did not designate any derivatives as hedges, under GAAP. Therefore, all changes in the fair value of derivative financial instruments are reflected in earnings. The following table presents the amounts affecting the consolidated statements of income for the three months and six ended June 30, 2012 and 2011.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_b3f99247_f064_4d56_9e18_5315a3ba58f9;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> <!--EndFragment--> </div> 0 0 429000 241000 179000 132000 <div> <!--StartFragment--> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><a name="_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866"><b>13. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS<font style="background:yellow;mso-highlight:yellow;"></font></b></a></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;">We and certain current and former officers and directors have been named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Court for the District of Colorado. The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purports to state claims under Section 10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April 2, 2007 and April 14, 2008 (the &#8220;Class Period&#8221;). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleges that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claims that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint seeks compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also added attorneys&#8217; fees and costs of litigation. On February 28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit.</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;"> </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;"></font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-name:Default;mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;mso-layout-grid-align:none;text-autospace:none;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;color:black;margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;">We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants have </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:windowtext;">entered into a Stipulation of Settlement</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;"> with the plaintiffs that would, if approved by the United States District Court for the District of Colorado, resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class, and plaintiffs&#8217; appeal would be dismissed. Our independent auditor is not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:windowtext;">is</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;"> subject to customary conditions, including</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:windowtext;"> preliminary court approval, and final</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;"> court approval following notice to stockholders.&nbsp; If the settlement becomes final, all amounts required by the settlement will be paid by our insurers. There can be no assurance that the </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:windowtext;">settlement</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;"> will be finally approved by the District Court</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;color:windowtext;">, or that approval by the District Court will, if challenged, be upheld by the Tenth Circuit</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;color:windowtext;">.&nbsp;</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">On October&nbsp;27, 2010, Spectrum Agencies (&quot;Spectrum&quot;) filed suit against our subsidiary, Crocs Europe B.V. (&quot;Crocs Europe&quot;), in the High Court of Justice, Queen's Bench Division, Royal Courts of Justice in London, United Kingdom (&quot;UK&quot;). Spectrum acted as an agent for Crocs products in the UK from 2005 until Crocs Europe terminated the relationship on July&nbsp;3, 2008 due to Spectrum's breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe. Spectrum alleges that Crocs Europe unlawfully terminated the agency relationship and failed to pay certain sales commissions. A trial on the liability, not quantum (compensation and damages), was held at the High Court in London from November&nbsp;30, 2011 to December&nbsp;5, 2011. On December&nbsp;16, 2011, the High Court of Justice issued a judgment that found that although Spectrum's actions were a breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe the breach was not sufficiently severe to justify termination. We believe that the trial judge erred in his findings and permission to appeal the judgment was requested. Given that this phase of the proceedings only pertains to liability, there have been no findings in relation to the amount of compensation or damages other than with respect to legal fees. Under UK law, the prevailing party is entitled to reimbursement of reasonable legal fees incurred in the liability proceedings. Spectrum has not quantified its claim for compensation and damages and the amount will be assessed later in the proceedings. Such assessment may be stayed pending the outcome of an appeal on liability. We were granted permission to appeal and </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">the appeal hearing took place on</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;"> July </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">4, </font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">2012</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">. We have not received a ruling from that hearing</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">.</font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;"></font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-fareast-font-family:Calibri;mso-fareast-theme-font:minor-latin;">We are currently subject to an audit by the U.S. Customs Service in respect of the period from 2006 to present. We anticipate that the U.S. Customs Service will present its audit report to us in the second half of 2012. At this time, we cannot accurately predict the ultimate outcome or estimate potential loss, if any, related to this matter. If an unfavorable outcome were to occur, it may result in substantial costs and a diversion of management's attention and resources that are needed to successfully run our business.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;">With respect to our outstanding litigation matters, we have accrued an aggregate of $<a name="_cf1fbeef_29e6_4075_9abc_d36159d707ed">0.4</a> million in Accrued expenses and other current liabilities on the consolidated balance sheets as of June 30, 2012.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;">While we intend to vigorously defend these matters, based on our current knowledge, it is reasonably possible that adverse outcomes could result in aggregate losses beyond accrued amounts. However, the outcome of such legal matters is inherently unpredictable and subject to significant uncertainties. Due to the nature of these legal proceedings we are currently unable to reasonably estimate a range of potential outcomes. </font><font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt;">If unfavorable final outcomes were to occur beyond amounts accrued, it may have a material adverse effect on our financial statements.&nbsp;</font></font></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_d2ee5b1e_b977_407b_92f0_a068f60a9866;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe will have a material adverse impact on our business.</font></font><!--EndFragment--> </div> 406000 397000 <div> <!--StartFragment--> <div align="center"> <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="width:100.0%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt: 0in 0in 0in 0in;"> <tr style="mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;height:1.0pt;mso-height-rule: exactly;"> <td width="80%" valign="bottom" style="width:80.8%;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in; Accordingly, these statements do not include all of the information and disclosures required by GAAP or SEC rules&nbsp;and regulations for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair presentation of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year. </font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">These statements should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and footnotes included in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 (the &#8220;2011 Form&nbsp;10-K&#8221;). The accounting policies used in preparing these unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements are the same as those described in Note&nbsp;1 - Summary of Significant Accounting Policies to the consolidated financial statements in the 2011 Form&nbsp;10-K. </font></font></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates, judgments and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Management believes that the estimates, judgments and assumptions made when accounting for items and matters such as, but not limited to, the allowance for doubtful accounts, sales returns and discounts, impairment assessments and charges, recoverability of assets (including deferred tax assets), uncertain tax positions, share-based compensation expense, useful lives assigned to long-lived assets, depreciation and provisions for contingencies are reasonable based on information available at the time they are made. Management also makes estimates in the assessments of potential losses in relation to threatened or pending legal and tax matters (see Note 13 &#8211; Legal Proceedings). Actual results could materially differ from these estimates. For matters not related to income taxes, if a loss is considered probable and the amount can be reasonably estimated, the Company recognizes an expense for the estimated loss. </font></font><!--EndFragment--> </div> 1722000 1762000 145583000 179979000 257587000 278827000 34396000 21240000 <div> <!--StartFragment--> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><a name="_25b2a9fd_aae6_4309_8bb2_1661b76f5733"><b>11. COMMITMENTS AND CONTINGENCIES</b></a></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_25b2a9fd_aae6_4309_8bb2_1661b76f5733;"><a name="_07de9ead_2fa7_4729_aebb_b4577a0d25e0"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">We lease space for certain of our offices, warehouses, vehicles and equipment under leases expiring at various dates through 2022. Certain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. </font></a><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">Rent expense for leases with step rents or rent holidays is recognized on a straight-line basis over the minimum lease term. Deferred rent is included in the consolidated balance sheet in accrued expenses and other current liabilities. Total rent expense was $<a name="_29d7191a_5312_434a_a8a0_1584ded9a314">26.8</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_b8125998_73b6_43ed_a646_9edf193a929b">21.4</a>&nbsp;million for the three months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011, respectively. Included in such amounts are contingent rents of $<a name="_9e42db3d_d7b0_4a40_8dcc_21e35c2c7771">6.6</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_f82a335a_5537_41ee_91e8_579d34def39f">5.0</a>&nbsp;million in 2012 and 2011, respectively. Total rent expense was $<a name="_b0a5a444_4e2b_4e06_bad7_e0a611c985d1">48.0</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_04d8a5c1_874a_4b0c_a278_cecbadf70b38">39.1</a>&nbsp;million for the six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011, respectively. Included in such amounts are contingent rents of $<a name="_96836088_361b_4e0e_98ca_ae93ffcf587b">8.7</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_4157c925_8e43_414e_9964_6728c2958f93">6.7</a>&nbsp;million in 2012 and 2011, respectively.</font></font><!--EndFragment--> </div> 0.001 0.001 250000000 250000000 90306432 90727610 89807146 90205424 90000 91000 82427000 56456000 84767000 50001000 232869000 125367000 261856000 134857000 1400000 800000 1600000 800000 7100000 3300000 2600000 1100000 7047000 7809000 30375000 30849000 2889000 3480000 14900000 7300000 11500000 6000000 19407000 4670000 2988000 1280000 8938000 6949000 3520000 9563000 2365000 1361000 670000 4396000 3365000 1802000 17257000 5183000 3202000 1292000 9677000 3061000 4519000 8904000 2948000 1475000 685000 5108000 1517000 2279000 During the first quarter of 2012, we changed the internal reports used by our CODM to align the definition of our segment operating income with Income (loss) from operations. Previously, segment operating income (loss) excluded asset impairment charges and restructuring costs not included in cost of sales. Segment operating income also reflects the reclassification of Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net, from Income (loss) from operations on the consolidated statements of income. See Note 1 – Basis of Presentation for further discussion. Segment information for all periods presented has been reclassified to reflect these changes. We lease space for certain of our offices, warehouses, vehicles and equipment under leases expiring at various dates through 2022. Certain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. Each of our reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear, apparel and accessories to external customers. <div> <!--StartFragment--> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><a name="_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9"><b>8. STOCK-BASED COMPENSATION</b></a></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;">Options granted generally vest on a straight-line basis over four years with the first year vesting on a cliff basis followed by monthly vesting for the remaining three years. Restricted stock awards and restricted stock units granted generally vest on a straight-line basis over three or four years depending on the terms of the grant. Stock-based compensation expense is recognized on a straight-line basis over the applicable vesting period and is recognized in the Cost of sales and Selling, general and administrative expense line items in the condensed consolidated statements of income. During the three months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011, $<a name="_85cf52e7_46ec_49a6_8019_0ade5f50e36e">4.0</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_c6d5a08e_5d69_44dd_80cc_6feebe96b595">2.4</a> million, respectively, of stock-based compensation expense was recorded, of which $<a name="_92b2525b_3d47_4504_a9f1_f5ee354ab2b8">0.6</a> million and $<a name="_8cd5e6d2_5f3f_4f46_a96f_9b28a1e5b4a6">0.3</a> million, respectively, was recorded in Cost of sales. During the six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011, $6.1&nbsp;million and $3.9 million, respectively, of stock-based compensation expense was recorded, of which $<a name="_34624de5_38b0_4f8b_bd30_4aef2053d908">1.0</a> million and $<a name="_651b8fc0_df3e_4b5b_be59_b35cc4edd983">0.6</a> million, respectively, was recorded in Cost of sales.</font></p> <p style="mso-bookmark:_db2cf0f7_a467_420e_9854_e52b44c12839;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_a4b6b0c8_453d_411c_9f18_9f8e8921a7f1;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_ddf85be4_5836_481f_be8d_ac4ad6a97dbc;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_318c580f_46c7_4a5d_ba10_cbba7d473334;"></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_9d6b6ef9_8f13_444a_bda7_d99e6b385f66;"></font> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;"><b style="mso-bidi-font-weight:normal;"><i style="mso-bidi-font-style:normal;">Restricted Stock Shares and Units</i></b></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">From time to time, we grant restricted stock shares and restricted stock units (&#8220;RSU&#8221;) to our employees. Unvested restricted stock shares have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested restricted stock shares cannot be transferred until they are vested. An unvested RSU is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock only upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but no voting rights.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;"><a name="_c876b3f3_321f_4b89_aa4d_78c445a32fc3"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">During the six months ended June 30, 2012, the Board of Directors approved grants of </font></a><a name="_353db0e3_2267_48d6_8bc9_e4af765a7a2b"><font style="mso-bookmark:_c876b3f3_321f_4b89_aa4d_78c445a32fc3;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">0.4</font></font></a></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_c876b3f3_321f_4b89_aa4d_78c445a32fc3;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;"> million RSUs to certain executives as part of a performance incentive program. <a name="_74db4d82_bbca_4548_bab1_c9347f38aa33">Half</a> of these grants vest ratably on each of the first three anniversaries of the grant date; <a name="_a85f32b9_8445_46a0_b6e2_2fbe8bc438b7">25</a>% will vest upon achievement of certain performance metrics; and the remaining <a name="_404c919c_307a_4201_b800_7c0516d447a4">25</a>% will vest one year from such date. If actual performance metrics exceed the targeted performance metrics by a predetermined amount, the executives are eligible to receive up to <a name="_208b13a4_78ae_401c_8530_a87c2ad2bb97">200</a>% of the performance-based portion of their award. </font></font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">During the three and six months ended June 30, 2012, $<a name="_c871ed78_bd43_4090_b385_0525eb3a6f71">0.1</a> million and $<a name="_5725b82e_7bb0_4b1a_b457_c2215b2f0a77">0.6</a> million, respectively, of share-based payment expense related to these RSUs was recorded.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan lines-together;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_71b2951b_b02c_4998_a17d_a22bf23016e9;">The following table summarize the restricted stock shares activity for the three and six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011. </font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan style="color:black;">23.93</font></a></font></font></font></p> </td> </tr> </table> </div> <!--EndFragment--> </div> 0.87 0.62 1.00 0.68 0.85 0.61 0.99 0.68 <div> <!--StartFragment--> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><a name="_2b34bea5_47cf_4cb0_a4c1_cc342a802f31"><b>10. EARNINGS (LOSS) PER SHARE</b></a></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:6.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_2b34bea5_47cf_4cb0_a4c1_cc342a802f31;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">For all periods presented, basic and diluted earnings (loss) per common share (&#8220;EPS&#8221;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings (loss) attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is an unvested share-based payment award containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends (whether or not declared) and must be included in the computation of earnings per share pursuant to the two-class method. Shares of unvested restricted stock are considered participating securities as they have non-forfeitable dividend rights. The following table sets forth EPS for the three and six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';page-break-after:avoid;mso-hyphenate:none;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_2b34bea5_47cf_4cb0_a4c1_cc342a802f31;"><font style="font-size:1.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></font></p> <div align="center"> <table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="width:100.0%;border-collapse:collapse;mso-yfti-tbllook:1184;mso-padding-alt: 0in 0in 0in 0in;"> <tr style="mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes;height:1.0pt;mso-height-rule: exactly;"> <td width="52%" valign="bottom" style="width:52.12%;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in; $<a name="_859c695a_e173_4b76_9e31_74baa021a856">7.3</a>&nbsp;million, respectively, in depreciation expense of which $<a name="_64b108cf_1e22_4d93_a69a_f212eea3130f">1.1</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_2f76b5de_4098_41ee_a262_8036722be1c1">3.3</a>&nbsp;million, respectively, was recorded in Cost of sales, with the remaining amounts recorded in Selling, general and administrative expenses in the condensed consolidated statements of income. During the six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011, we recorded $<a name="_7aaeca7f_5bee_424c_8a33_90a3a1577882">11.5</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_189c8b0d_2cf8_4ca5_bdb9_a17c8fbec3c4">14.9</a>&nbsp;million, respectively, in depreciation expense of which $<a name="_cc3e4118_0290_4bab_a5ca_8e12a888fd15">2.6</a>&nbsp;million and $<a name="_5f0ec73d_449d_47fe_900f_9bb0a8bbebe9">7.1</a>&nbsp;million, respectively, was recorded in Cost of sales, with the remaining amounts recorded in Selling, general and administrative expenses in the condensed consolidated statements of income.</font></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_8ac41800_772e_4f63_ac69_2c4f486fafd6;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">We periodically review all of our stores for indicators of impairment. During the three and six months ended June 30, 2012, we determined that certain underperforming domestic stores in the Americas segment were unlikely to generate sufficient cash flows to recover the carrying value of the stores&#8217; assets over the remaining economic life of those assets. As a result, we recorded impairment charges of $<a name="_694d2a19_2fcd_4b9b_959a_0956a062d701">0.1</a> million and $0.8 million during the three and six months ended June 30, 2012, respectively, to adjust the carrying value of these store assets to our estimate of their fair value, which is based on our estimate of future discounted cash flows. During the six months ended June 30, 2011, an insignificant amount of impairment charges were recorded which related to our Sendai, Japan retail store as a result of the March 2011 Japanese earthquakes. style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in .5in 1.0in;"><a name="_5c1ec8da_5bcb_45ca_9a80_60c21d96725e"><b>12. OPERATING SEGMENTS AND GEOGRAPHIC INFORMATION</b></a></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:4.5pt;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_5c1ec8da_5bcb_45ca_9a80_60c21d96725e;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">We have <a name="_275ac6ab_f009_4491_a1fc_9846130136c6">three</a> reportable operating segments: Americas, Europe and Asia. We also have an Other businesses category which aggregates insignificant operating segments that do not meet the reportable threshold and represent manufacturing operations located in Mexico and Italy. The composition of our reportable operating segments is consistent with that used by our chief operating decision maker (&#8220;CODM&#8221;) to evaluate performance and allocate resources. <a name="_202d102c_74ab_43c0_916e_a1dfeb4ce494">Each of our reportable operating segments derives its revenues from the sale of footwear, apparel and accessories to external customers.</a> Revenues of the Other businesses category are primarily made up of intersegment sales which are eliminated when deriving total consolidated revenues. The remaining revenues for the Other businesses represent non-footwear product sales to external customers. Segment assets consist of cash and cash equivalents, accounts receivable and inventory.</font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_5c1ec8da_5bcb_45ca_9a80_60c21d96725e;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">Segment operating income (loss) is the primary measure used by our CODM to evaluate segment operating performance and to decide how to allocate resources to segments. Segment performance evaluation is based primarily on segment results without allocating corporate expenses, or indirect general, administrative and other expenses. Segment profits or losses of our reportable operating segments include adjustments to eliminate intersegment profit or losses on intersegment sales. </font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:12.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0in;margin-left:0in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_5c1ec8da_5bcb_45ca_9a80_60c21d96725e;"><a name="_ed79f041_04f3_4cee_97b8_d694e8f33462"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">During the first quarter of 2012, we changed the internal reports used by our CODM to align the definition of our segment operating income with Income (loss) from operations. Previously, segment operating income (loss) excluded asset impairment charges and restructuring costs not included in cost of sales. Segment operating income also reflects the reclassification of Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses, net, from Income (loss) from operations on the consolidated statements of income. See Note 1 &#8211; Basis of Presentation for further discussion. Segment information for all periods presented has been reclassified to reflect these changes.</font></a></font></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_ed79f041_04f3_4cee_97b8_d694e8f33462;"></font> <p style="mso-style-unhide:no;mso-style-qformat:yes;mso-style-parent:'';margin:0in;margin-bottom:.0001pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:10.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-hyphenate:none;tab-stops:-.5in;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_5c1ec8da_5bcb_45ca_9a80_60c21d96725e;">The following tables set forth information related to our reportable operating business segments during the three and six months ended June 30, 2012 and 2011.</font></p> <p the six months ended June 30, 2012, the Board of Directors approved grants of 0.4 million RSUs to certain executives as part of a performance incentive program. Half of these grants vest ratably on each of the first three anniversaries of the grant date; 25% will vest upon achievement of certain performance metrics; and the remaining 25% will vest one year from such date. BASIS OF PRESENTATION</b></a></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><a name="_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively, &#8220;we,&#8221; &#8220;us,&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221;) are engaged in the design, manufacture and sale of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children. </font></a></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#8220;GAAP&#8221;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#8220;SEC&#8221;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. Accordingly, these statements do not include all of the information and disclosures required by GAAP or SEC rules&nbsp;and regulations for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair presentation of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year. </font></font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">These statements should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and footnotes included in the Company&#8217;s Annual Report on Form&nbsp;10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2011 (the &#8220;2011 Form&nbsp;10-K&#8221;). The accounting policies used in preparing these unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements are the same as those described in Note&nbsp;1 - Summary of Significant Accounting Policies to the consolidated financial statements in the 2011 Form&nbsp;10-K. </font></font></font></p> <p style="mso-style-priority:99;mso-style-unhide:no;margin:0in;margin-bottom:6.0pt;mso-pagination:widow-orphan;font-size:12.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';"><font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_e3393537_bc7f_46f9_8d4b_1b3aee5af8d9;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates, judgments and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expenses during the reporting period. Management believes that the estimates, judgments and assumptions made when accounting for items and matters such as, but not limited to, the allowance for doubtful accounts, sales returns and discounts, impairment assessments and charges, recoverability of assets (including deferred tax assets), uncertain tax positions, share-based compensation expense, useful lives assigned to long-lived assets, depreciation and provisions for contingencies are reasonable based on information available at the time they are made. Management also makes estimates in the assessments of potential losses in relation to threatened or pending legal and tax matters (see Note 13 &#8211; Legal Proceedings). Actual results could materially differ from these estimates. For matters not related to income taxes, if a loss is considered probable and the amount can be reasonably estimated, the Company recognizes an expense for the estimated loss. </font></font></font><font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;"></font></font></p> <font style="mso-bookmark:_37456705_9bad_4ec4_8652_4fbb4333309b;"><a name="_dc366071_e589_4d64_a999_09cdb394a9c5"><b><i><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;">Reclassifications</font></i></b><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;"> &#8211; Certain prior period amounts on the consolidated condensed financial statements have been reclassified to conform to current period presentation. We reclassified the Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses line item from Income (loss) from operations to Income (loss) before income taxes in the consolidated statements of income. We also reclassified (gains) losses on our derivative contracts from Other (income) expense to the Foreign currency transaction (gains) losses line item. As a result of these reclassifications, Income (loss) from operations increased $</font></a><a name="_433b6ea4_eeec_4190_bc2b_8cec5cbfeaa4"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;"><font style="mso-bookmark:_dc366071_e589_4d64_a999_09cdb394a9c5;">3.0</font></font></a><font style="mso-bookmark:_dc366071_e589_4d64_a999_09cdb394a9c5;"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;"> million and $<a name="_2b2ea020_9d49_42fa_b160_c4b2633da94d">1.7</a> million for the three and six months ended June 30, 2011, respectively, from the amounts previously reported.</font></font><font style="font-size:10.0pt;font-family:'Times New Roman','serif';mso-fareast-font-family:'Times New Roman';mso-ansi-language:EN-US;mso-fareast-language:EN-US;mso-bidi-language:AR-SA;"> These reclassifications did not affect net income.</font></font><!--EndFragment--> </div> 491780000 583680000 1259680 918129 285444 179250 499286 522186 19759000 19930000 44500000 44200000 89617 89895 90550 90613 87656 88029 89413 89519 Corporate and other assets primarily consist of cash and equivalents. Includes $1.0 million and $0.7 million of accumulated amortization of software held under a capital lease as of June 30, 2012 and December 31, 2011, respectively. Includes $4.1 million of software held under a capital lease classified as capitalized software as of June 30, 2012 and December 31, 2011. Includes a corporate component consisting primarily of corporate support and administrative functions, costs associated with share-based compensation, research and development, brand marketing, legal, depreciation and amortization of corporate and other assets not allocated to operating segments and costs of the same nature related to certain corporate holding companies. Includes entrusted loan payable balances of $11.2 million and $9.1 million as of June 30, 2012 and December 31, 201l, respectively, for which a corresponding $11.2 million and $9.1 million are recorded in Prepaid expenses and other current assets, respectively, as entrusted loan receivables related to our subsidiaries in China.
